<article>
    <h1>Where to chill BAL&#xAD;LADS FOR THE BRO&#xAD;KEN-HEARTED</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201106/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-06"><time>2020-11-06</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE |  WEEKEND</span>
        - <span role="byline">LOVE GOES</span>
    </section>

    <p>POP/R&B</p>
    <p>Sam Smith</p>
    <p>“Put your hands in the air if you some­times ever get sad like me,” sings Sam Smith on So Se­ri­ous, a track off the English singer’s third stu­dio al­bum, Love Goes.</p>
    <p>But on a record that in­vites the lis­tener to dance through the pain of heart­break, the song is barely a salve for the bro­ken-hearted, when com­pared to Swedish pop star Robyn, who has per­fected the art of sad songs over elec­tropop beats. In con­trast, Smith’s ef­fort feels a bit tame.</p>
    <p>The songs do not quite have the dancier sounds of pre-al­bum singles How Do You Sleep and Danc­ing With A Stranger. The only hints that Love Goes has veered to­wards a more ex­per­i­men­tal dance record are on tracks like Di­a­monds and Dance (Til You Love Some­one Else).</p>
    <p>In­stead, the al­bum de­liv­ers on the tried-and-tested Sam Smith brand of heart-on-sleeve ro­man­tic mis­ery and de­spair-filled bal­ladry, with gloomy lyrics like “Don’t it make you sad, that we’ll never be kids again?”</p>
    <p>Smith’s ex­tra­or­di­nary falsetto shines as usual, as the singer trades vo­cal gym­nas­tics with fel­low Brit Labrinth on the ti­tle track, which crescen­dos into a eu­phoric au­dio ex­plo­sion of strings, horns and beats.</p>

